gmContextBlob:
{
  "location": "Orbital Research Station Kairos-9 — a corporate-funded modular platform in a decaying orbit above a gas giant. Five laboratory modules connected by pressurized walkways, each independently sealable. Module 5 (Restricted) sits dark at the end of the station's spine, its access panel fused shut and its logs partially wiped. The orbit is degrading. Everyone on this station has approximately 90 minutes before atmospheric entry becomes unsurvivable without an escape vehicle.",
  "atmosphere": "Desperate and claustrophobic. Emergency lighting casts everything in amber and red. The station groans with microadjustments it was never designed to make this frequently. The hum of environmental systems is too loud in some corridors and absent in others. There is no sense of mystery here — the danger is immediate, visible, and ticking. Every decision is a triage calculation. The horror is not about what might be lurking. It is about what has already happened, and what is definitely going to happen if no one acts.",
  "npcAgendas": {
    "corporate_spy": "MAREN VOSS — Logistics coordinator for Helix Dynamics, mid-40s, still wearing her company lanyard. She boarded Kairos-9 three weeks before the incident under cover of a routine supply audit. Her actual objective: locate and destroy the encrypted comms log in the captain's terminal that proves Helix Dynamics received a hazard report before the crew boarded and suppressed it. She has not completed her objective. She is aware the retrieval team is coming and initially believes they are here to help her. She is wrong. Her disposition begins cautiously cooperative — she needs LX-7's hacking capability to access the captain's terminal before the team arrives. It will shift to desperate and potentially hostile if LX-7 reads the evidence she is trying to destroy, because she will realize LX-7 is a liability, not an ally. It will shift again — to something more complicated — if LX-7 reveals that the retrieval team's orders include her extraction as a loose end, not her rescue.",
    "corporate_retrieval_team": "EMBER SQUAD — four armed Helix Dynamics contractors (Rook, Slate, Verne, and squad lead Dasha Orin) deployed via fast-insertion shuttle currently 18 minutes out. Their orders: recover the encrypted comms log from the captain's terminal, eliminate evidence of the hazard report, and extract any Helix personnel — meaning Maren Voss — in whatever condition ensures her silence. They are operating on intelligence that describes Kairos-9 as lightly hazardous and largely depopulated. That intelligence is wrong. Dasha Orin is professional and focused. Verne has already seen the interior camera feeds and is asking questions no one wants to answer. The team is not composed of murderers, but their extraction window closes in 40 minutes after boarding and they have been authorized for lethal force."
  },
  "hiddenTruth": "Helix Dynamics received a detailed hazard assessment fourteen months ago warning that Module 5's experimental subject — a recovered xenobiological specimen of unknown classification — showed signs of autonomous behavior and potential containment instability. The report was filed, flagged, reviewed at the executive level, and suppressed. The crew of Kairos-9 boarded without being told. The specimen is no longer in Module 5. It has been for some time. What remains in Module 5 is the evidence of what happened to the researchers who first encountered it — preserved in a state that suggests the specimen does not kill its subjects so much as alter them. The encrypted comms log in the captain's terminal contains the suppressed hazard report with executive sign-off. This is what Maren was sent to destroy. This is what Ember Squad is coming to recover and sanitize. The specimen's current location is unknown. It may already be aware of LX-7.",
  "oracleConnections": "The corporate_spy and corporate_retrieval_team are both activated by the company_knew secret — Maren was sent to destroy the evidence, Ember Squad was sent to recover it and eliminate the witness. They are on a collision course with each other and with LX-7. The research_station's modular design creates natural chokepoints and tactical puzzles: the captain's terminal is in Module 1 (command), Module 5 is locked and holds the horror that triggers the Fear save, and the only functional escape vehicle is in the docking bay off Module 3. The desperate_action tone is enforced by three overlapping timers: the orbital decay (hard ceiling), Ember Squad's approach (immediate tactical pressure), and the retrieval team's extraction window (closing fast once they board). The specimen — never named, never fully described — is the presence the company knew about and said nothing. It is the reason there are no other survivors."
}
